 needs and rights of children and young people. Leading authors write from a variety of backgrounds and disciplines including social policy, education, geography and sociology. The book critically examines the concepts of participation and social inclusion and their links with children and childhoods and considers the geography of social inclusion and exclusion. It explores young people's own conceptualisations of social inclusion and exclusion; and examines how these concepts have been expressed in policy at various levels. The book concludes with an agenda for progressing participation and social inclusion, both for and with children and young people. Children, young people and social inclusion will be of interest to academics, students and policy makers, as well as to a wide range of practitioners including teachers, youth workers, participation workers and those working in interagency settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChildren with social disabilitieszGreat Britain. 0aChildrenzGreat BritainxSocial conditions. 0aChildren's rightszGreat Britain. 0aSocial integrationzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBell, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirchall, Johnston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCairns, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdwards, Rosie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Malcol